"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Corinthians chapters 11-13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2corinthians-11-13.py

Context decisions for chs 11-13:
- The 'Fool's Speech' (11:1-12:13) parodies Greco-Roman epideictic rhetoric
  (the speech of self-praise). Paul performs the boast-form to demolish it.
- 'Super-apostles' (hoi hyperlian apostoloi): Hellenistic Jewish itinerant
  missionaries using letters of recommendation and Sophistic-style display.
- Peristasis catalogue (11:23-33): a recognized Stoic-Cynic rhetorical form;
  the philosopher-sage demonstrates virtue through endured hardship.
- Aretas IV of Nabataea (11:32): extra-biblical corroboration; dates Damascus
  episode to ca. 37 CE. Aretas ruled 9 BCE - 40 CE.
- Third heaven / paradise (12:2-4): Jewish apocalyptic cosmology (1 Enoch,
  2 Enoch, Testament of Levi, b.Hagigah 14b).
- Thorn in the flesh (12:7): skolops te sarki — identification debated;
  candidates include ophthalmia, epilepsy, speech impediment, spiritual
  torment. The point is the unremoved nature, not the identification.
- Two or three witnesses (13:1): Deut 17:6; 19:15 — legal testimony standard
  applied to the structure of Paul's visits.
- The closing triad (13:14): earliest explicit Trinitarian blessing in Paul.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>The request to \'bear with a little foolishness\' (<em>aphrosyne</em>) signals the opening of the Fool\'s Speech (11:1-12:13), a sustained parody of Greco-Roman epideictic rhetoric. <em>Epideixis</em> (display speech) was a recognized rhetorical genre: the sophist or wandering teacher would offer a public demonstration of his credentials, often through self-praise (<em>autepainesis</em>). Quintilian and Plutarch both discuss the technique. Paul does not simply refuse to boast — he performs the boast in an exaggerated, self-undermining mode to expose its absurdity while simultaneously conveying autobiographical data that defends his ministry.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The betrothal image — presenting the community as a virgin bride to one husband — draws on OT covenant language where Israel is the bride of YHWH (Hos 2:19-20; Isa 54:5; Ezek 16). The father\'s role in arranging a daughter\'s betrothal was a standard Roman and Jewish legal function (<em>patria potestas</em>). Paul presents himself as the father/friend of the bridegroom (cf. John 3:29) who has betrothed the Corinthians to Christ. Godly jealousy (<em>zelos theou</em>) echoes the jealousy of YHWH in Exod 20:5 — the exclusive covenant claim of the divine husband on his bride.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Eve\'s deception by the serpent\'s cunning (<em>panourgia</em>) references Gen 3:1-6. The LXX uses <em>phronimos</em> (prudent/clever) for the serpent in Gen 3:1, but Paul chooses <em>panourgia</em> (cunning, unscrupulous cleverness) — the same word he used of himself sarcastically in 12:16. The serpent\'s technique was theological misdirection: offering \'a different gospel\' (different knowledge about God). Paul applies this prototype to the super-apostles\' activity: their \'different Jesus, different Spirit, different gospel\' (v.4) is the contemporary form of Eden\'s original deception.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The \'different Jesus... different spirit... different gospel\' formula is Paul\'s sharpest polemical characterization of the rival missionaries. The terminology \'Jesus\' without \'Christ\' may be deliberate — a Jesus defined by earthly power and rhetorical sophistication rather than crucifixion and resurrection. The Corinthians\' willingness to tolerate this alternative reveals their susceptibility to the epideictic appeal: impressiveness as the criterion of apostolic validity. Paul\'s criteria throughout 2 Corinthians are consistently different: suffering, weakness, and resurrection-life through death.</p>',
    "5": '<p>\'Super-apostles\' (<em>hoi hyperlian apostoloi</em>): the Greek is ironic and probably Paul\'s coinage. The term likely refers to the rival missionaries in Corinth, not to the Jerusalem apostles (whom Paul treats respectfully in Gal 2:1-10). These figures were probably Hellenistic Jewish itinerant teachers with Syrian or Palestinian origin who arrived bearing written credentials (<em>epistolai systatikai</em>, cf. 3:1) and demonstrated their apostolicity through rhetorical performance and miraculous signs. Paul\'s claim not to be \'in the least inferior\' (<em>ouden hystereke</em>) uses the language of comparison that the Sophistic tradition thrives on.</p>',
    "6": '<p>\'Untrained as a speaker\' (<em>idiotes to logo</em>): <em>idiotes</em> = a non-professional, private person, layman — someone without formal rhetorical training. This is a concession to the Corinthians\' criticism that Paul was unimpressive in person (10:10: his bodily presence is weak and his speech contemptible). Rhetoric was a professional skill taught in schools; the Sophists charged fees for public displays of their craft. Paul acknowledges the criticism but insists on knowledge (<em>gnosis</em>): he may lack the performer\'s polish, but he possesses genuine theological understanding that he has demonstrated to them in every way.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The accusation implicit in Paul\'s rhetorical question: was it wrong to preach free of charge? In the Greco-Roman world, accepting payment from a patron was the normal mechanism for validating a speaker\'s social status and creating a reciprocal obligation. The Sophists charged fees; clients expected to pay for services rendered. Paul\'s refusal of payment from Corinth was interpreted by some as either lack of confidence in his message or — worse — as evidence that he lacked the patronal status that came with payment. Paul turns the argument: preaching free of charge elevated them, not him.</p>',
    "8": '<p>\'I robbed other churches\' (<em>allaas ekklesias esylaesa</em>): <em>sylaw</em> = to plunder, strip of armor (a military image). Paul supported himself in Corinth through funds from Macedonian churches (specifically Philippi, Phil 4:15-16). This is confirmed by Acts 18:5, which notes that when Silas and Timothy arrived from Macedonia (presumably with funds), Paul devoted himself full-time to preaching. The \'robbery\' language is deliberately hyperbolic — Paul accepted support from one set of churches to serve another.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The \'brothers who came from Macedonia\' are probably the Philippian co-workers who brought financial support during Paul\'s Corinthian ministry (Acts 18:5; Phil 4:16). Paul\'s refusal to burden the Corinthians financially stands in contrast to the rival missionaries who apparently accepted financial support from the community (cf. 11:20: they exploit you). The self-support and Macedonian-support practice is a deliberate apostolic posture, not mere financial necessity.</p>',
    "10": '<p>\'As surely as the truth of Christ is in me\' (<em>aletheia Christou en emoi</em>): a mild oath formula, less intense than 1:23 but still an appeal to divine verification. The boast about refusing payment will continue throughout the region of Achaia. Achaia was the Roman province comprising much of southern Greece, with Corinth as its capital. Paul\'s apostolic practice of free preaching is a matter of public record across the province, not just in Corinth.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The rhetorical question \'because I do not love you?\' and the answer \'God knows I do\' functions as a <em>captatio benevolentiae</em> (appeal for goodwill) — a standard rhetorical move at the beginning of a defense speech. Paul preemptively denies the inference that refusing payment signals indifference. The appeal to God\'s knowledge (<em>theos oiden</em>) recurs throughout 2 Corinthians (1:23; 5:11; 11:31; 12:2-3) as Paul grounds his self-presentation in the court of divine knowledge rather than Corinthian perception.</p>',
    "12": '<p>\'To cut the ground from under those who want an opportunity\': <em>aphorme</em> (opportunity, base of operations) — the same word Paul used in 5:12 when he gave the Corinthians ammunition against the boasters. The rival missionaries want to be \'found equal\' (<em>eurethosi kathows kai hemeis</em>) with Paul — to be validated on the same terms. Paul refuses: by maintaining his free-preaching policy, he denies them the comparison they seek. If they also refuse payment, they lose their support; if they accept it, they are exposed as different from Paul.</p>',
    "13": '<p>\'False apostles, deceitful workers\' (<em>pseudapostoloi, ergatai dolioi</em>): Paul\'s sharpest attack on the rivals. <em>Pseudapostolos</em> appears only here in the NT. <em>Dolioi</em> (deceitful) recalls the serpent\'s cunning (<em>panourgia</em>) of v.3. \'Masquerading as apostles of Christ\' (<em>metaschematizomenoi eis apostolous Christou</em>): <em>metaschematizo</em> = to change the form, to disguise. This is the language of theatrical costume-change — the rivals wear the form of apostleship without the substance.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The <em>a minori ad maius</em> (from lesser to greater) argument: if Satan himself disguises himself as an angel of light (<em>angelos photos</em>), no wonder his servants do the same. The Jewish tradition of Satan as a deceptive angelic figure appears in the Testament of Job 6, Life of Adam and Eve 9, and later rabbinic sources. The \'angel of light\' motif may also connect to Paul\'s contrast in 4:4-6: the adversary blinds minds to the light of the gospel; counterfeit messengers carry the same anti-light function in a different mode.</p>',
    "15": '<p>\'Their end will be what their actions deserve\' (<em>to telos... kata ta erga auton</em>): the eschatological judgment of the false apostles. The phrase is deliberately compressed — Paul avoids spelling out the condemnation in detail, but the implication of damnation is clear. \'Servants of righteousness\' (<em>diakonoi dikaiosyne</em>) as their self-presentation — the same term Paul uses for his own ministry (3:9; 6:7) — is applied to the rivals as a disguise rather than a reality.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The resumption of the fool-speech (<em>aphron</em> = mindless, lacking sense): Paul repeats the framing before launching the actual boast. The double invitation — if you take me for a fool, receive me as one — is the rhetorical move of <em>synkrinein</em> (comparison), the method by which orators demonstrated superiority by listing credentials against a rival. Paul will perform the form while signaling throughout that the whole enterprise is foolish (<em>kata sarka</em>).</p>',
    "17": '<p>\'Not as the Lord would speak but as a fool\' (<em>ou kata Kyrion alla hos en aphrosyne</em>): this meta-commentary is unusual — Paul steps outside the speech to label what he is doing. The Fool\'s Speech has a built-in disclaimer: this is not how the Lord speaks; this is the mode of worldly boasting. The disclaimer makes the speech self-referentially ironic. Paul is doing what he condemns while condemning it, exposing the futility of the entire epideictic enterprise.</p>',
    "18": '<p>\'Since many are boasting in the way the world does\' (<em>kata sarka</em> — according to flesh): Paul aligns the rivals\' boasting practice with the Corinthians\' worldly evaluation standards. The \'many\' who boast kata sarka are the Sophistic competitors who fill Corinth\'s marketplace. Corinth in the first century was a cultural crossroads where traveling teachers, philosophers, and rhetoricians competed for audiences and patrons. Paul\'s boasting will match the form but expose the content\'s absurdity.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Biting irony: \'you gladly put up with fools since you are so wise\' (<em>phronimoi ontes</em>). The Corinthians pride themselves on wisdom (1 Cor 1:26-31 is still the background), yet they tolerate the foolishness of competitive self-promotion from the rivals. The irony cuts both ways: the Corinthians\' supposed wisdom makes them susceptible to the very foolishness that genuine wisdom would reject.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The catalogue of abuses the Corinthians tolerate from the rivals: enslave (<em>katadouloo</em>), devour (<em>katestheio</em>), take advantage of (<em>lambanei</em>), put on airs (<em>epairesetai</em>), slap in the face (<em>derei eis prosopon</em>). The slap in the face was a Roman legal gesture of domination — <em>vindicatio</em>, the formal taking of possession. These are not metaphors: Paul describes actual patron-client exploitation of a community conditioned by Sophistic patronage norms to accept humiliation from powerful teachers. The rivals\' domination of the Corinthians fits the Sophistic teacher-student dynamic.</p>',
    "21": '<p>\'To my shame I admit we were too weak for that\' — the irony reaches its peak: Paul\'s gentleness and refusal to exploit appear as \'weakness\' by the rivals\' standards. The transition to the Fool\'s Speech proper: \'whatever anyone else dares to boast about — I also dare\' (<em>tolmo kago</em>). The competitive boasting (<em>synkrinein</em>) begins. The phrase \'speaking as a fool\' (<em>en aphrosyne lego</em>) is the running disclaimer throughout the speech (vv. 17, 21, 23).</p>',
    "23": '<p>The peristasis catalogue (11:23-33) is a recognized rhetorical form in Stoic-Cynic tradition: the philosopher demonstrates superiority by recounting hardships endured with equanimity. Epictetus, Dio Chrysostom, and Seneca all employ versions of the peristasis. Paul\'s catalogue is unique in its autobiographical specificity and in the way it inverts the Sophistic logic: whereas the Stoic peristasis proves the sage\'s inner strength, Paul\'s catalogue proves his weakness as the locus of divine power (12:9-10). The sheer quantity of afflictions overwhelms any competitor.</p>',
    "24": '<p>\'Forty lashes minus one\' (<em>tessarakonta para mian</em>): the Jewish flogging formula. Deut 25:3 limits flogging to 40 strokes; the rabbis reduced this to 39 as a safety margin against miscounting (m.Makkoth 3:10-14). This means Paul submitted to synagogue discipline five times — suggesting ongoing involvement with Jewish communities throughout his missionary career, not a clean break from Jewish life. Each flogging presupposes his presence in a synagogue context and his subjection to Jewish juridical authority.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Three beatings with rods (<em>rhabdizo</em>): Roman military punishment, used by lictors who accompanied magistrates. Acts records the Philippi beating (Acts 16:22-23); the other two are unattested elsewhere. Stoning (<em>lithazo</em>): Acts 14:19 records the Lystra stoning. Shipwrecked three times: Acts records only the Malta shipwreck (Acts 27), which occurs after this letter — all three mentioned here predate Acts\' account, emphasizing how selective Acts\' narrative is. Night and day in the open sea (<em>en to bytho</em>): the deep, the abyss — clinging to wreckage or floating debris, entirely exposed.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The geography of danger in v.26 maps Paul\'s entire missionary theater: rivers (winter flash floods on Anatolian roads), bandits (provincial roads were notoriously dangerous; the Pax Romana extended primarily to cities), fellow Jews, Gentiles, city dangers, country dangers, sea, false brothers. The term \'false brothers\' (<em>pseudadelphoi</em>) echoes Gal 2:4 — infiltrators in the community who posed as believers. The catalogue is not merely rhetorical padding; each item represents specific experiences with specific threats in specific places.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Labor and toil (<em>kopos kai mochthos</em>) — the double formula for exhausting manual work recurs in 1 Thess 2:9 and 2 Thess 3:8, confirming Paul actually performed manual labor (tentmaking/leatherworking, Acts 18:3). Cold and nakedness (<em>psyche kai gymnoteti</em>): outdoor exposure, not merely insufficient clothing. These physical details connect to 4:8-9\'s peristasis language and demonstrate that the apostolic weakness on display in 4:7-12 is literally embodied, not rhetorical.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Beyond the external hardships: \'the daily pressure of concern for all the churches\' (<em>he merimna pason ton ekklesion</em>). <em>Merimna</em> (anxiety, pressing concern) — the same word used by Paul in Phil 4:6 when he tells the community not to be anxious. Paul himself carries the pastoral anxiety he tells others to release. The \'all the churches\' claim indicates the scope of his apostolic responsibility extends far beyond Corinth — a claim that implicitly challenges the legitimacy of missionaries whose concern is limited to one community.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Pastoral identification with weakness and sin: \'who is weak, and I do not feel weak?\' (<em>tis asthenei kai ouk ego asthenoo</em>). The apostle\'s solidarity with the community\'s moral struggles is a form of pastoral <em>sympatheia</em> (feeling-with). \'Who is led into sin, and I do not inwardly burn?\' (<em>pyroymai</em> — burn with indignation, zeal, passion): whether the burning is empathetic grief or jealous anger for the person led astray, the apostle experiences it with them. This is the emotional dimension of \'concern for all the churches\' in v.28.</p>',
    "30": '<p>\'If I must boast, I will boast of the things that show my weakness\' (<em>ta tes astheneias mou kauchesomani</em>): the pivot of the Fool\'s Speech. Having performed the competitive boasting catalogue (credentials, hardships, imprisonment, beatings), Paul announces that his genuine boast is weakness itself. This is the fundamental inversion of the Sophistic boast: the rival missionaries boast of strength; Paul boasts of weakness. The Damascus basket episode immediately illustrates this inversion.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The oath formula: \'the God and Father of the Lord Jesus, who is to be praised forever, knows I am not lying\' (<em>theos oiden hoti ou pseudomai</em>). Paul invokes a blessing formula over God (<em>ho on eulogetos eis tous aionas</em>) — a doxological form from Jewish liturgy (cf. Rom 9:5). The oath grounds the truthfulness of the Damascus account in God\'s knowledge. The oath appears before the Damascus story — before v.32-33 — which suggests Paul considered the story potentially unbelievable without divine attestation.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The Damascus escape (11:32-33) is corroborated externally. Aretas IV Philopatris ruled Nabataea from 9 BCE to 40 CE; his territory bordered and at times included Damascus. Josephus confirms Aretas IV\'s regional power (Ant. 18.5.1-3). The dating of this event to ca. 37-40 CE provides one of the few absolute chronological anchors for Pauline biography, correlating with Gal 1:17-18 (Paul in Arabia, then Damascus). Nabataean control of Damascus in this period is attested by the absence of Tiberian coins from Damascus — suggesting Rome granted Aretas control during 37-40 CE.</p>',
    "33": '<p>Lowered in a basket from a window in the wall (<em>sargane</em> — a braided rope-basket, used for produce or cargo). The image is deliberately undignified: the great apostle escaping like contraband goods. Acts 9:25 gives the same account (the disciples lowered him in a basket). Paul opens the Fool\'s Speech with a boast of weakness and closes it with a story of flight — the opposite of a military triumph. The contrast with the Roman triumphal procession of 2:14 is pointed: there, God leads Paul in triumph; here, Paul escapes in a basket. Both images define apostolic service as anti-heroic by worldly standards.</p>'
  },
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>The transition from the escape narrative to the heavenly ascent: \'I must go on boasting — although there is nothing to be gained, I will go on to visions and revelations.\' The heavenly ascent (12:2-4) is a genre of Jewish apocalyptic literature. <em>1 Enoch</em>, <em>2 Enoch</em>, the <em>Testament of Levi</em> 2-3, and <em>4 Ezra</em> all feature heavenly journeys in which the seer ascends through multiple heavens and receives divine revelations. By the first century, multiple-heaven cosmologies were well established in Jewish thought. Paul\'s account is notably reticent: he does not report what he saw or heard.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The double statement of ignorance — \'whether in the body or apart from the body I do not know, but God knows\' — repeats for emphasis. Paul cannot determine whether the experience was visionary (a trance-like state) or actual bodily transport. Both possibilities were live options in Jewish apocalyptic: some traditions described the visionary as transported bodily (1 Enoch 39:3), others as experiencing an ecstatic out-of-body state. Paul\'s agnosticism here is itself significant — the experience was so overwhelming that ordinary categories of embodied/disembodied consciousness did not apply.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Paradise (<em>paradeisos</em>): the Persian loanword (pairi-daeza = enclosed garden) appears in the LXX for the Garden of Eden (Gen 2:8-10) and for the eschatological garden of God (Isa 51:3; Ezek 28:13; 31:8-9). In intertestamental literature, paradise became the realm of the righteous dead or the eschatological reward. The Talmud (b.Hagigah 14b) records the \'four who entered pardes\' — Ben Azzai, Ben Zoma, Acher, and Akiba — a rabbinic tradition about mystical ascent that may echo the same traditions Paul draws on. \'Inexpressible things\' (<em>arreta rhemata</em>) — things not permitted to speak: the concealment of heavenly secrets is standard in Jewish apocalyptic (1 Enoch 14:3; Rev 10:4).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The deliberate self-distancing: \'I will boast about that person, but not about myself, except about my weaknesses.\' Paul speaks of the heavenly-ascent experience in third person (\'a man in Christ\') — a rhetorical distancing that signals this is not normal Sophistic self-promotion. The ascent is real, but Paul will not leverage it the way a Sophistic wonder-worker would. The rival missionaries apparently emphasized visionary experience and spiritual power as credentials; Paul relativizes the ascent experience entirely by immediately pivoting to the thorn (12:7).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Paul\'s reason for restraint in heavenly boasting: so no one will think more of me than what they observe (<em>blepei me e akouei ex emou</em> — sees or hears from me). This is the anti-Sophistic epistemology of 2 Corinthians: apostolic credibility comes from observable conduct and audible message, not from claimed supernatural experiences that cannot be verified. The visible Paul — weak, persecuted, free-preaching — is the Paul to be evaluated. The heavenly visionary Paul must be bracketed for the sake of honest apostolic relationship.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The thorn in the flesh (<em>skolops te sarki</em>): <em>skolops</em> can mean a stake, a pointed instrument, a splinter, or a thorn. The phrase \'messenger of Satan\' (<em>angelos Satana</em>) suggests either a demonic agent of affliction or a person who was Satan\'s instrument in harassing Paul. Identifications proposed by modern scholars include: ophthalmia (eye disease, suggested by Gal 4:13-15 where Paul implies the Galatians would have given him their eyes), epilepsy, malaria, a speech impediment, sexual temptation, or severe depression. The ambiguity is probably intentional — Paul does not want the thorn identified with a specific condition but understood as a structural feature of apostolic weakness.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Three times Paul appealed to the Lord (<em>ton Kyrion parekalesa</em>): the triple petition echoes Jesus\' Gethsemane prayer (Matt 26:36-44: three times Jesus prayed for the cup to pass; it did not). The pattern of unanswered petition followed by divine reassurance of sufficient grace is a defining moment in Paul\'s theology: prayer is not a mechanism for removing divine-permitted suffering but an encounter with the God who redeems suffering by inhabiting it.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The divine response: \'my grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness\' (<em>he dynamis mou en astheneia teleitai</em>). This is one of the rare direct divine speech-acts in Paul\'s letters. The structure — grace sufficient, power perfected in weakness — reverses the Sophistic credentials: where rivals demonstrate power through strength, God demonstrates power through Paul\'s weakness. The thorn is not removed because the unanswered prayer, the ongoing weakness, is the very locus of divine power-display. Paul\'s subsequent \'boasting in weaknesses\' is theologically grounded here.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The delight in weaknesses (<em>astheneia</em>), insults (<em>hybris</em>), hardships (<em>anagkais</em>), persecutions (<em>diogmois</em>), difficulties (<em>stenochoriois</em>) — a five-item peristasis variation. <em>Hybris</em> (insults, arrogant mistreatment) was a legal category in Athenian and Roman law: deliberate degradation of a person\'s honor. That Paul lists it alongside physical hardships shows the social-honor dimension of apostolic suffering — not just pain but public dishonor. The closing principle: \'when I am weak, then I am strong\' (<em>hotan gar asthenoo, tote dynatos eimi</em>) — the paradox that defines the Fool\'s Speech entire.</p>',
    "11": '<p>\'You drove me to it\' (<em>hymeis me enagkasate</em>): the Corinthians\' failure to defend Paul against the rivals forced the Fool\'s Speech. The community\'s passivity in the face of the rivals\' attacks constituted an implicit endorsement of the Sophistic evaluation criteria. \'I am not in the least inferior to the super-apostles, even though I am nothing\' (<em>oudenos hystereka ton hyperlian apostolon, ei kai ouden eimi</em>): the double move — superior and nothing. The rhetorical comparison paradox: Paul beats the rivals at their own game of comparison while simultaneously declaring that the comparison game itself is worthless.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The signs of an apostle (<em>semeia tou apostolou</em>): the community is the proof. Signs, wonders, and miracles (<em>semeiois te kai terasin kai dynamesin</em>) were performed among them. The triple formula for miraculous works (cf. Acts 2:22 of Jesus; Heb 2:4) was the recognized evidential basis for apostolic claims in the early church. Paul acknowledges this criterion — the rivals apparently emphasized it — while placing it firmly in the past and pointing to suffering and weakness as the present evidence of genuine apostolicity.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The ironic \'wrong\' of not accepting payment: \'how were you inferior to the other churches, except that I was never a burden to you? Forgive me this wrong\' (<em>charisasthe moi ten adikian tauten</em>). The sarcasm is pointed. In the patronage economy, a teacher who refused payment from a wealthy patron was depriving that patron of the opportunity to display their generosity and social status. By refusing Corinthian support, Paul was arguably insulting them by denying them the honor of being his benefactors. The ironic apology acknowledges this cultural dynamic while maintaining the policy.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Third visit announced: this confirms that a second, painful visit (mentioned in 2:1) occurred between 1 and 2 Corinthians. Paul\'s apostolic relationship to the community is familial: parents save up for children, not the reverse. The Roman family was the basic unit of economic provision: <em>patria potestas</em> gave the father authority and responsibility over the household. Paul inverts the Sophistic economic relationship (teacher charges clients) with the parental model: he expends himself for them as a father for children.</p>',
    "15": '<p>\'I will very gladly spend and be entirely spent (<em>dapaneso kai ekdapanethisomai</em>) for your lives.\' The double verb is intensifying: spend (resources) and be spent (self). The voluntary self-expenditure language echoes 4:12\'s \'death is at work in us, life in you\' — the apostle as the one who is consumed so that the community may live. The rhetorical question \'if I love you more, will you love me less\' expresses genuine pastoral vulnerability — Paul is not cynically performing love but genuinely wounded by the asymmetry.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The accusation Paul addresses: even though he accepted no payment, he was crafty (<em>panourgos</em>) and caught them by trickery (<em>doloo</em>). The charge may be that Paul received support through Titus or others while maintaining the appearance of financial independence. <em>Panourgos</em> (all-working, unscrupulously clever) is the adjective form of <em>panourgia</em> (cunning, 11:3; 4:2) — the very quality Paul attributed to the serpent and the false apostles. Now his accusers turn the same word back on him.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The rhetorical question about Titus and the other brother: did Paul exploit the Corinthians through his envoys? The question expects a negative answer — both Titus and the unnamed brother behaved with integrity. This defends against the charge of v.16: if Paul were exploiting through agents, his agents would have shown it. The parallel conduct of Paul and Titus in financial matters (<em>to auto pneumati periepatesamen</em>) is offered as evidence of consistent apostolic integrity.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Titus and the anonymous brother walked \'in the same footsteps\' (<em>tois autois ichnesin</em>): the metaphor of following in someone\'s tracks or steps (<em>ichnos</em>) was used for disciples following a teacher\'s way of life. Paul and his co-workers constitute a school of apostolic conduct characterized by non-exploitation and free service. This consistency across multiple persons is evidence against the accusation of covert manipulation.</p>',
    "19": '<p>\'Have you been thinking all along that we have been defending ourselves to you?\' The meta-commentary: the Fool\'s Speech was not a legal <em>apologia</em> (defense before a court) but an act of apostolic construction (<em>oikodome</em>). The community is the audience before whom Paul speaks, not the judge. \'We have been speaking in the sight of God as those in Christ\' — the defense is oriented toward divine accountability, not human verdict. The purpose of the speech was their building up, not his acquittal.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The fear of finding the community in disorder: a vice catalogue (quarreling, jealousy, anger, selfishness, slander, gossip, conceit, disorder — <em>eris, zelos, thymos, eritheia, katalalia, psithyrismos, physiosis, akatastasiai</em>). This list of eight social vices maps the dysfunction of a community shaped by Sophistic patronage competition. The rival missionaries\' presence has not improved Corinthian community life; it has intensified the status-competition and social fragmentation that Paul\'s first letter already addressed.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The feared personal humiliation: \'my God will humble me before you\' (<em>tapeinosei me ho theos mou</em>). The mourning over those who have sinned (<em>proemartekoton</em>) and not repented suggests specific known members of the community who engaged in sexual immorality (<em>aselgeia, porneia, akatharsia</em>). The Corinthian sexual ethics problem (1 Cor 5-7) apparently persisted despite the earlier letter\'s instructions. Paul\'s grief is pastoral, not punitive: he mourns over the unrepentant before he confronts them.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>\'Every charge must be established by the testimony of two or three witnesses\' cites Deut 17:6 and 19:15 (LXX). Paul applies the Mosaic legal standard to the structure of his visits: the third visit will constitute the third \'witness\' in Paul\'s ongoing testimony to the community. In Jewish legal procedure, the two-or-three-witness rule was the foundational standard for any capital case or disciplinary action. By framing his third visit in these terms, Paul signals that this visit will function as a legal proceeding with binding consequences.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The warning given on the second (painful) visit is now repeated by letter — \'while absent\' (<em>apon</em>) — in lieu of Paul\'s present voice. The combination of written warning now and promised direct action when present (\'I will not spare\') replicates the legal pattern of formal warning followed by action. \'Those who sinned earlier and all the others\' (pas tous loipous): the discipline will be comprehensive, not limited to the original offenders. The parousia-announcement of Paul\'s coming functions as an eschatological warning within the letter\'s rhetorical structure.</p>',
    "3": '<p>\'Since you are demanding proof that Christ speaks through me\' (<em>dokimen zetountes tou en emoi lalountos Christou</em>): the proof-demand is the climax of the rivalry dispute. The rivals apparently cast doubt on Paul\'s apostolic credentials by challenging the authenticity of Christ\'s voice in his ministry. Paul\'s response: \'he is not weak in dealing with you but is powerful among you.\' The power they seek (signs, rhetorical displays) is already present among them in Christ\'s community-forming work — Paul merely mediated it.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The Christ-was-crucified-in-weakness paradox: the epistemological basis for Paul\'s ministry of weakness. Christ\'s crucifixion was a demonstration of weakness by every Roman social standard — the condemned criminal hanging in public shame (Cicero Pro Rabirio 5.16 calls crucifixion the most extreme penalty reserved for non-citizens). Yet he \'lives by the power of God\' (<em>ze ek dynameoas theou</em>). Paul\'s apostolic existence follows the same pattern: weak in Christ, yet powerful by the same resurrection-power when dealing with the community\'s need. Weakness and power coexist in the apostolic and Christological mode.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The self-examination instruction: \'examine yourselves\' (<em>heautous peirazetie</em>). <em>Peirazete</em> = to test, try, put to the proof — the same root as the \'testing\' of Jesus in the wilderness (Matt 4:1) and of faith in James 1:2. The community is invited to apply to themselves the test they wanted to apply to Paul. \'Do you not realize that Jesus Christ is in you?\' (<em>en hymin</em>) — the apostolic test reverses: the community\'s own inner life is the evidence for Christ\'s presence and therefore for the apostle\'s authenticity. If Christ is in them, he got there through Paul\'s ministry.</p>',
    "6": '<p>\'I hope you will discover that we have not failed the test\' (<em>hoti hemeis ouk esmen adokimoi</em>): adokimos = failing the test, counterfeit (as of base metal failing the assay). The irony: Paul hopes the Corinthians\' self-examination will simultaneously vindicate Paul\'s apostolicity — because the Christ in them was implanted through Paul\'s gospel. The community\'s spiritual life is Paul\'s credentialing evidence; the super-apostles who have not founded the community have no comparable evidence.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Paul\'s stated preference is not to demonstrate apostolic power through discipline but for the community to do what is right on its own. The prayer is for their moral integrity, not for the opportunity to exercise authority. \'Even if we appear to have failed the test\' (<em>hemeis de hos adokimoi omen</em>) — even if Paul appears powerless (because no discipline was needed), that is acceptable if the community is living rightly. The apostle\'s power is always exercised for building up, not for demonstration (<em>oikodomein eis oikodomen</em>).</p>',
    "8": '<p>\'We cannot work against the truth, only for it\' (<em>ou gar dynametha ti kata tes aletheias, alla hyper tes aletheias</em>): a gnome (general maxim) that grounds all apostolic practice in the truth\'s own direction. The apostle cannot exercise authority contrary to the truth — not because of personal limitation but because the truth itself constrains and orients all genuine apostolic work. If the community is walking rightly, Paul can only rejoice, not find occasions to punish.</p>',
    "9": '<p>\'We are glad whenever we are weak and you are strong\' — the reversal of competitive rhetoric: Paul\'s gladness in his own weakness is genuine when it corresponds to the community\'s strength. The prayer for \'your complete restoration\' (<em>hymon katartisin</em>): <em>katartisis</em> (from <em>katartizo</em> = to mend, restore, put in order; used for mending nets in Matt 4:21) — the community as a net that needs repairing, or as a dislocated joint being set back in place. Complete restoration is the pastoral goal, not punishment or apostolic vindication.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The letter\'s stated purpose: written while absent so Paul need not be harsh when present. The authority (<em>exousia</em>) given by the Lord is for building up (<em>oikodome</em>), not tearing down (<em>kathairesis</em>) — a principle stated in 10:8 and restated here to close the letter\'s argument. The authority to build up is the governing constraint on all apostolic power: if Paul must use authority destructively (exercising judgment), something has already gone wrong in the community. The preferred outcome is always the upbuilding that makes discipline unnecessary.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The closing exhortations cluster Greek imperatives: \'farewell/rejoice\' (<em>chairete</em>), \'aim for restoration\' (<em>katartizesthe</em> — the same root as 13:9\'s <em>katartisis</em>), \'encourage one another\' (<em>parakaliesthe</em>), \'be of one mind\' (<em>to auto phroneite</em>), \'live in peace\' (<em>eireneuete</em>). The final four are all present imperatives — ongoing community practices, not one-time acts. The promise: \'the God of love and peace will be with you\' (<em>ho theos tes agapes kai eirenes estai meth\' hymon</em>) — the character of God (agape and eirene) corresponds to the community\'s called practice.</p>',
    "12": '<p>\'Greet one another with a holy kiss\' (<em>en hagio philemati</em>): the holy kiss appears in all four of Paul\'s closing greetings (Rom 16:16; 1 Cor 16:20; 1 Thess 5:26; here) and in 1 Pet 5:14. The kiss was a standard Mediterranean greeting gesture for family members and close associates — Paul applies it to the community of believers as a sign of fictive kinship in Christ. It also functioned liturgically: Justin Martyr (First Apology 65) describes the kiss of peace as part of the eucharistic assembly. The practice bridges private greeting and public worship.</p>',
    "13": '<p>\'All God\'s people here send their greetings\' — the community with Paul (probably in Macedonia) co-signs the greeting. This counters the implicit claim of the rivals that they represent a larger apostolic network: Paul writes not alone but with a community behind him. The plural senders also ground the letter in a specific church context, not just in an individual apostle\'s authority.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The closing Trinitarian benediction: \'the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ, the love of God, and the fellowship of the Holy Spirit\' (<em>he charis tou Kyriou Iesou Christou kai he agape tou theou kai he koinonia tou hagiou pneumatos</em>). This is the most explicit three-person blessing formula in Paul\'s letters and one of the earliest Trinitarian formulas in Christian literature. The three gifts are matched to the three persons: <em>charis</em> (grace) to Christ, <em>agape</em> (love) to God, <em>koinonia</em> (fellowship, participation) to the Spirit. The order — Christ, God, Spirit — is not subordinationist but reflects the order of Christian experience: encounter with Christ (through the gospel) leads to the knowledge of God\'s love and to participation in the Spirit\'s life.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2corinthians')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2corinthians', existing)
    for ch in ['11', '12', '13']:
        count = len(existing.get(ch, {}))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {count} entries')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
